

HTML Generator
--------------

This service is pointed at an HTML template file and given a set
of parameters with values, then creates an output HTML file (in
the location specified) where the parameters in the template have
been updated with the values.

There are facilities for including external files verbatim (e.g.
standard headers and footers) and for formatting ASCII tables
into HTML.  The text below the line is an example template.

--------------------------------------------------------------------
</html>

This is am example of the templating for a table file. The normal
parameter handling stuff still works: \parm1\ and \parm2\ but now you
can include a table file reference.

<table>
<tr>
   <td>RA</td>
   <td>FNU 12</td>
   <td>RA versus FNU 12</td>
   <td>FNU 25</td>
   <td>Dec</td>
</tr>
\%tblfile\
<tr>
   <td>\ra\</td>
   <td>\fnu_12\</td>
   <td>\ra\ / \fnu_12\</td>
   <td>\fnu_25\</td>
   <td>\dec\</td>
</tr>
\%%\
</table>

The table header is up to the user.  The table records start getting
processed when a "%ref" is found.  For each record in the table, the
following block of text is replicated, with the references replaced by
the corresponding table column record value.  The block defining a
record template ends with a "%%" reference.

This can be run with, <i>.e.g.</i>:

<pre>
#!/bin/sh

htmlgen             \\ 
   test.template    \\
   tbl.html         \\
   parm1   example1 \\
   parm2   example2 \\
   tblfile test.tbl 
</pre>


</html>
